This article discusses an executive order issued by President Barack Obama, titled "Making Open and Machine Readable the New Default for Government Information." The order emphasizes the importance of openness in government, stating that making information resources easy to find, accessible, and usable can fuel entrepreneurship, innovation, and scientific discovery. It highlights the success of making weather data and the Global Positioning System freely available in the past, which led to the creation of various useful products and businesses. The order states that the default state of new and modernized government information resources should be open and machine readable, promoting government efficiency and job growth. It also emphasizes the need to safeguard individual privacy, confidentiality, and national security. The order directs various agencies and officials to implement an Open Data Policy, which includes publishing an online repository of tools and best practices, integrating the policy requirements into federal acquisition and grant-making processes, and establishing a Cross-Agency Priority Goal to track implementation. The order concludes by stating that it does not impair any existing authorities or functions, and it is subject to applicable law and availability of appropriations.